        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>20</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0036/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>0036</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/0036/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Boolean valuations: negation">Boolean valuations: negation</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>         The scheme we'll start with is a very standard one.
        These valuations are often called `Boolean valuations', after the logicians George and Mary Everest Boole, although there are some small differences from the logical approach they developed.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>20</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0037/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0037</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/0037/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>George and Mary Everest Boole lived and wrote in England and Ireland in the 19th century, and Mary into the 20th as well.
George is typically credited alone for the logical work he published, but I think it's worth noting that Mary was an author in her own right, their relationship was clearly an intellectual one, and George's most influential book, <html:em>The Laws of Thought</html:em>, was written during the time their relationship was beginning.
So I think it's entirely likely that Mary had some influence on George's work, although how much and of what kind is something I could only speculate on.</html:p>
                <html:p>         Incidentally, here's Mary Everest Boole's advice for students encountering infinity:</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>3</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/001B/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>001B</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/001B/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Quotation</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>"Angels, and square roots of negative quantities, and the other things that have no existence in three dimensions [she later explicitly includes infinity as an angel], do not come to us to gossip about themselves; or the place they came from; or where they are going to; or where we are going to in the far future. They are messengers from the As-Yet-Unknown; and come to tell us where we are to go next; and the shortest road to get there; and where we ought not to go just at present. 
        When square root of minus one comes to you, behave reasonably about him. 
        Treat him logically, exactly as if he were six or nine; only always remember to keep well in front of you <html:em>the fact of your own ignorance</html:em>. 
        You may never find out any more about him than you know now; but if you treat him sensibly he will tell you plenty of truths about your <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>s and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>s, and other unknown things".</html:p>
                    <html:p>From Mary Everest Boole, <html:em>Philosophy and Fun of Algebra</html:em>, 1909.</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>         And here's her advice for me (and maybe also for you):</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>20</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0038/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>0038</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/0038/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Quotation</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>"You may some day become a teacher. 
        If ever you are teaching a class how to set down a sum or an equation, say 'This is my way', or 'This is the way which I think you will find most convenient', or 'This is the way in which the Government Inspector requires you to do the sums at present, and therefore you must learn it'. 
        But do not take in vain the names of great unseen powers to back up either your own limitations, or your own authority, or the Inspector's authority. 
        Never say, or imply, 'Arithmetic requires you to do this; your sum will come wrong if you do it differently'. 
        Remember that arithmetic requires nothing from you except absolute honesty and patient work. You get no blessing from the Unseen Powers of Number by slipshod statements used to make your own path easy."
</html:p>
                    <html:p>From Mary Everest Boole, <html:em>Philosophy and Fun of Algebra</html:em>, 1909.</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>This last one, I think, is of some importance when it comes to logic.
Unfortunately, the world has no shortage of people who are tempted to say "<html:em>Logic</html:em> tells us..." and then they fill in something they're trying to convince you of.
<html:strong>Don't fall for it.</html:strong>
Logic is about carefulness, orientation to detail, and discerning what you do and don't have support for.
It does not require you to believe or disbelieve <html:em>anything</html:em>.
(Rant over.)
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>         To calculate the value that a compound sentence takes on a given valuation, we need to know two things: the main connective of the sentence, and the values that its components take on the valuation.
        For Boolean valuations, here's how the dependence goes.
        If we have a negation---that is, a sentence whose main connective is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex>---then that sentence takes the opposite value from its component.
        So if we have a valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg \neg  p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg \neg \neg  p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and so on.
        I'll use a table like the following to record this:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>21</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/003J/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>003J</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/003J/</fr:route>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
    <html:thead><html:tr>
        <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex></html:td>
        <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr></html:thead>
    <html:tbody>
        <html:tr>
            <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
            <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
        </html:tr>
        <html:tr>
            <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
            <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
        </html:tr>
    </html:tbody>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p> This table tells you, for any value that a sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> might have on a Boolean valuation, what value the sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> must then have on that Boolean valuation.
    To use the table, if you know the value that a sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has on a Boolean valuation, find the row in the table that displays that value in the "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>" column.
    Then you can read the value that that same row has in the "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex>" column to see what value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> must have.
        Boolean negation is simple enough that you probably won't need this table for very long, or maybe not at all; but we'll look at other options in a moment, so it's good to be able to read a table like this.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         Why this table, rather than some other?
        That is, why have we chosen to set things up so that negations always take the opposite value from their components, rather than, say, always the same value, or always <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, or always <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>?
        (Note that those are the only four options, given our setup.)
        Those other options are all perfectly good options for a unary connective.
        The reason we've gone with the one we have is that we want <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> to have something to do with <html:em>negation</html:em>, with the idea of something <html:em>not</html:em> being the case.
        The truth-value-reversal idea we've gone with is one way to try to get at that.
        In English, if I say that the moon is made of green cheese, then what I've said is false; and so if I say it's <html:em>not</html:em> made of green cheese, then what I've said is true.
        The idea is to try to endow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> with a meaning at least something like the meaning of "not"; and this particular table is one attempt to do that, probably the best choice we can make given our current limitations.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
